{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2bfaf7dd-2faa-461e-b01e-fda9d1fc209d","content":"No project found in the working directory, but here's the answer:\n\nCreate a `.vscode/mcp.json` file in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for local MCP servers).\n- **`command` / `args`** — uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, replace `command` with the path to the executable and drop the `args`.\n\nMake sure your server reads from stdin and writes to stdout using the MCP protocol (e.g., via the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package with `UseStdioServerTransport()`). Don't write logs to stdout — use stderr instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0746c516-c3ed-4728-b559-b93fc9917411","outputTokens":263,"requestId":"5051:38FA8B:DCC8C4:FCBE68:69F2AB3C"},"id":"aa511e28-9936-4421-b68e-2ca16ba9460f","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:07:16.094Z","parentId":"7f73903f-36ca-402b-9dad-8a7f1679eafa"}
